Supplementary Code (explained). Movement-driven modeling reveals new patterns in disease transmission networks

Introduction

In this document, we present the workflow for reproducing the analysis. The following code can be used to obtain the results shown in the main document starting from any telemetry data, enabling the reproduction of the analysis for other species, diseases, and ecosystems with a few modifications. To minimize changes in the code, we recommend organizing the starting telemetry data for each study area with one row per GPS location and with the following columns:

  • ID: Individual identifier
  • SP: Species
  • lat: Location latitude (WGS 84)
  • long: Location longitude (WGS 84)
  • TIME: Location time of the day
  • DATE: Location date

However, other data structures can also be used if modifying the code.

Note that we carried out the analysis for two study areas: Doñana National Park (DNP) and Sierra de San Pedro (SSP). Although the workflow is designed for one study area, results for both study areas are presented, with repeated code hidden for better understanding.

1. Data preparation

We considered different survival rates of the pathogen in the environmentfor each season in the DNP system. Therefore, we divided each individual data per season. In our case, the locations are taken at a constant time interval, making them a valid input for moveSTIR. In the event that our data does not have a constant time interval, either due to configuration or operational errors, the use of the CTMM package (Calabrese et al. 2016) may be useful to adjust them to a constant interval (see Calabrese et al. 2016; Wilber et al. 2022). CTMM also allows for resampling trajectories at a shorter time interval than used in location recording (see Yang et al. 2023), although we did not use it in this case to avoid biases derived from inferring the trajectory between two locations.

MoveSTIR models each pair of individuals separately, so we need to generate a .csv document with the GPS data of each individual.

Required changes:

  • Line 11: Date and time format.
  • Line 12: Time zone
  • Lines 18-35: Skip if the analysis is not by season.
  • Line 37: Output name.
  • Line 46: Directory for storing the trajectories.

# Python code
get_season <- function(dates) {
  WS = as.Date("2000-1-1", format = "%Y-%m-%d") # Winter Solstice
  SE = as.Date("2000-4-1",  format = "%Y-%m-%d") # Spring Equinox
  SS = as.Date("2000-7-1",  format = "%Y-%m-%d") # Summer Solstice
  FE = as.Date("2000-10-1",  format = "%Y-%m-%d") # Fall Equinox
  
  # Convert dates from any year to 2000 dates
  d = as.Date(strftime(dates, format="2000-%m-%d"))
  
  ifelse (d >= WS & d < SE, "W",
          ifelse (d >= SE & d < SS, "SP",
                  ifelse (d >= SS & d < FE, "SU", "F")))
}
dat$season <- get_season(dat$date_time)
unique(dat$season)
dat$ID <- paste0(dat$ID, "_", dat$season)

    select(id, x, y, time_s)

}

2. Temporal decay

MoveSTIR takes into consideration the decay of pathogens in the environment. It must be estimated for each case. We calculated the rate of decay of animal TB in both environments (DNP and SSP) based on mean temperatures, which is the most influential factor (Jackson et al., 1995; Fine et al., 2011). We applied exponential regression to the available data from Jackson et al. (1995) and Fine et al. (2011) and computed values for our study areas. For DNP, we computed one value for each season, while for SSP, we computed one value for the entire montanera period (October to February).

data <- data.frame(Reference = c("Jackson et al. 1995", "Jackson et al. 1995", 
                                 "Jackson et al. 1995", "Fine et al. 2011", 
                                 "Fine et al. 2011", "Fine et al. 2011"), 
                   Temp = c(18.1, 8.3, 17.7, 0.4, 2.8, 21.8), 
                   Days = c(4, 21, 11, 29.88, 29.06, 6.88))

3. Relative risk modeling by MoveSTIR (Python)

MoveSTIR can be loaded as Conda environment in Conda or Anaconda. Here we shown the Python code for our analysis.

  • Line 49: Trajectories directory.
  • Line 61: Output directory.
  • Lines 80-100: Pathogen survival.

# Setting initial paramters:

# - Pathogen survival in the environment (further down)
# - Location (for the paths and for pathogen survival further down)
# - Time interval on the trajectories (set on CTMM)

disease = "TB"  # it could be other modifying the code below
location = "doñana"
time_interval = "2h"

# Reading the database
dat = pd.read_csv(
  "C:/Files/IREC/PhD/redes/Datasets_{0}/gps_loc_movestir_{1}.csv". 
  format(location,location))

# Converting date and time in an integer form
# The result is in nanoseconds so it's divided by 60*10^9 for obtaining 
# minute scale
dat = (dat.assign(datetime=lambda x: pd.to_datetime(x.date_time))
              .assign(unix_time = lambda x: x.datetime.astype(np.int64) / (60 * 10**9)))

# Individuals' (hosts) index
host_keys = np.unique(dat.ID)

# Reading trajectories
# Time is in seconds so it is divided by 60 for obtaining minute scale
all_fitted = {}
for h in host_keys:
            af = pd.read_csv(
              "C:/Files/IREC/PhD/redes/Datasets_{2}/data_{1}/traj_{0}.csv".
              format(h,time_interval,location))
            af = af.assign(time=lambda x: x.time_s / 60)
            af = af[["x", "y", "time"]]
            all_fitted[h] = af

host_keys = list(all_fitted.keys())

# Running moveSTIR for obtaining transmission kernels
host_keys = list(all_fitted.keys())
n = len(host_keys)

path = "C:/Files/IREC/PhD/redes/trans_kernels_{0}/{1}".format(location, time_interval)

count = 1

# moveSTIR works by pairs of hosts, repeating the loop for the inference of the
# kernel for every individual being host 1 (i) and every individual being 
# host 2 (j)
for i, h1_nm in enumerate(host_keys):
    for j, h2_nm in enumerate(host_keys):
        
        if i != j:
            logger.info("{0} of {1}".format(count, n*(n - 1)))
            logger.info("Working on {0} lag {1}".format(h1_nm, h2_nm))
            host1 = all_fitted[h1_nm].copy()
            host2 = all_fitted[h2_nm].copy()

            host1, host2 = stir.align_trajectories(host1, host2)
            nt = len(host1)
            
            # Here we can modify pathogen survival and distance decay according 
            # to location or pathogen
            if disease == 'TB':  # Conditionals must be added here if 
                                 # multiple diseases are included
            if location == 'extremadura':
                days_permanence = 12

            elif location == 'doñana':
                if 'SU' in h1_nm:
                    days_permanence = 4
                elif 'F' in h1_nm:
                    days_permanence = 9
                elif 'W' in h1_nm:
                    days_permanence = 13
                elif 'SP' in h1_nm:
                    days_permanence = 7
                        
            if location == 'extremadura':
                distance_decay = 26
            elif location == 'doñana':
                distance_decay = 52
                
            # Pathogen decay in minute scale
            pathogen_decay = 1 / (24 * 60. * days_permanence)
            dd_type = 'cutoff'
            
            # Running transmission kernels
            # Transmission kernels are heavy, so we use memory mapping to process
            # them to avoid lack of RAM capacity issues following recommendations
            # on Wilber et al. (2022).
            # For our interest, we save from each transmission (host1 from host2) 
            # two csv files:
            # direct_indirect FOI csv:
                # column 1: relative FOI for each step in the temporal window 
                # (i.e. time gap between visits by the depositor and the acquirer)
                # relative to their total FOI.
                # column 2: time for each time step
            # total FOI csv:
                # column 1: total FOI for each time step
                # column 2: time for each time step
            # After extracting the info, the kernel is deleted, 
            try:
                
                datapath = os.path.join(path, "K_{0}lag{1}.dat".format(h1_nm, h2_nm))
                deltat, K_1lag2, _ = stir.transmission_kernel(host1, host2,
                pathogen_decay, distance_decay, dd_type=dd_type, max_size=1,
                file_path=datapath)
                                
                Kmat = np.memmap(datapath, dtype=np.float32, mode="r", 
                shape=(nt, nt))
                
                column_1 = np.array([np.sum(np.diagonal(Kmat.T, 
                offset=offset)*deltat) 
                for offset in np.arange(Kmat.shape[0])])
                  column_2 = host1.time.values*60
                  df = pd.DataFrame({'FOI':column_1, 'time':column_2})
                  df.to_csv(os.path.join(path,
                  "direct_indirect_{0}_from_{1}.csv".format(h1_nm, h2_nm,)), 
                  index=False)
                
                column_1 = (Kmat*deltat).sum(axis=1)
                df = pd.DataFrame({'FOI':column_1, 'time':column_2})
                df.to_csv(os.path.join(path,
                "total_{0}_from_{1}.csv".format(h1_nm, h2_nm,)),index=False)
            
                        
                del (Kmat)
            
                try:
                    os.remove(datapath)
                except FileNotFoundError:
                    pass
                
            except IndexError:
                    print("Error for {0} and {1}. No overlap".format(h1_nm, h2_nm))

4. \(λ\) and \(β\) estimations

\(λ\) (deposition rate) and \(β\) (acquisition rate) refer to the amount of pathogen deposited and acquired by hosts per unit of time. They must be estimated for each case. As is often the case with wildlife pathogens, we did not have these estimates, so we estimated \(λ\) and \(β\) by comparing the excretion and infectious dose of each species, and the percentage of infected animals that spread the pathogen. While this approach provides a relative measure of the transmission risk between species, it does not enable us to determine the actual risk of transmission. We extended the information regarding wild boar to Iberian pigs and the information regarding red deer to fallow deer.

We took the highest excretion dose (\(ed\)) as reference, and estimated the excretion rates (\(λ\)) for an individual of the species \(i\) as: \[ λ_i =p_i·ed_i/ed_{ref} \] Being:

  • \(p_i\) the proportion of infected animals of the \(i\) species that seed the pathogen,
  • \(ed_i\) the pathogen excretion dose of the \(i\) species, and
  • \(ed_{ref}\) the pathogen excretion dose of reference.

For the \(β\), we considered the highest proportional value (1) when the infectious dose (\(id\)) was equal to the excretion dose of reference, and a linear decline in the FOI with the decrease of the infectious dose. Therefore, the acquisition rate (\(β\)) for an individual of the species \(i\) is estimated is: \[ β_i = ed_{ref}/id_i \] Being:

  • \(id_i\) the pathogen infectious dose of the i species , and
  • \(ed_{ref}\) the pathogen excretion dose of reference.

Therefore, we our estimates for \(λ\) and \(β\) are:

param <- data.frame(Species = c("Wild boar/Iberian Pig", "Cattle", 
                                "Red deer/Fallow deer"), 
                    Reference = c("Santos et al., 2015; Ballestero et al., 2009",
                                  "Neill et al., 2001; McCorry et al., 2005; 
                                  Griffin et al., 2006", "Griffin et al., 2006; 
                                  Santos et al., 2015"), 
                    "% of shedders" = c(79.5, 70.1, 92.9), 
                    "Excretion dose (CFU/ml)" = c(1.82*10^2, 9*10^1, 8.37*10^1), 
                    "Infectious dose (CFU/ml)" = c(10^3, 5*10^2, 5*10^2),  
                    check.names = FALSE)
param$λ <- round((param$`% of shedders`/100)*param$`Excretion dose (CFU/ml)`/
                   max(param$`Excretion dose (CFU/ml)`), digits = 2)
param$β <- round(max(param$`Excretion dose (CFU/ml)`)/
                   param$`Infectious dose (CFU/ml)`, digits = 2)

5. Loading data

Hereafter the analysis is carried out in a single R script. Firstly, all the trajectories are loaded into the R environment and put together in a single object. As is often the case with wildlife telemetry studies, not all animals were marked during the same period of time. Hence, each pair of individuals overlapped for different amounts of time, so individuals that overlapped for longer periods were more likely to be exposed to each other, resulting in higher FOI estimates. To account for this, we divided the FOI by the amount of time that the monitoring of individuals overlapped.

Required changes:

  • Lines 16-18: locations and sampling interval.
  • Line 23: Telemetry data directory.
  • Line 33: MoveSTIR output directory.
  • Lines 57-79: λ and β estimates for each species.
  • Line 117: Join the dataframes created for each study area and sampling interval.

# Defining deposition and acquisition rates
location = c("doñana", "extremadura")       # locations
tint = c("2h", "10min")                     # sampling intervals
filetype = "total"                          # direct_indirect or total

# Loop for preparing the databases by location and time
for (m in location){                        # for all locations
  for (n in tint){                          # for all sampling intervals
    dat <- read.csv(paste0("C:/Files/IREC/PhD/redes/Datasets_",m,
                           "/gps_loc_movestir_", m, ".csv"))
    host_keys <- unique(dat$ID)             # host IDs
    assign(paste0("dat_", substr(m, start = 1, stop = 2)), dat)
    foi_list <- list()                      # Empty list
    
# Loop for loading trajectory files
    for (i in host_keys){                   # Host 1
      for (j in host_keys){                 # Host 2
        try({
          a <- read.csv(paste0("C:/Files/IREC/PhD/redes/trans_kernels_", m,
                               "/",n,"/", filetype,"_",
                               i,"_from_",j,".csv"))   # Name of the csv
          names(a) <- c("kernel", "datetime")          # Exposure, date and time
          a$vart <- 1:nrow(a) - 1                   # time step
          a$host1 <- i                              # Host 1
          a$host2 <- j                              # Host 2
          a$datetime <- as_datetime(a$datetime)     # seconds to date and time
          a$h1_species <- dat[dat$ID == i,]$SP[1]   # Host 1 species
          a$h2_species <- dat[dat$ID == j,]$SP[1]   # Host 2 species
          nlist <- paste0("foi_",i,"_",j)           # Name in the list
          foi_list[[nlist]] <- a                    # Add data frame to the list
        }, silent = TRUE)
      }
    }
   
    try({ 
# Compiling all the trajectories in a single dataframe    
    foi_contact <- Reduce(rbind, foi_list)
    
# Variable with both hosts
    foi_contact$hosts <- paste(foi_contact$host1, "_from_", foi_contact$host2)
    
# Including excretion and acquisition
    foi_contact$lambda <- as.numeric(ifelse(foi_contact$h2_species ==
                                              "Wild boar" |
                                              foi_contact$h2_species == "Pig",
                                            0.8, ifelse(
                                              foi_contact$h2_species == "Cattle",
                                              0.35, ifelse(
                                                foi_contact$h2_species ==
                                                  "Red deer" |
                                                  foi_contact$h2_species ==
                                                  "Fallow deer",
                                                0.43, "ERROR"))))
    
    foi_contact$beta <- as.numeric(ifelse(foi_contact$h1_species == 
                                            "Wild boar" |
                                            foi_contact$h1_species == "Pig",
                                          0.18, ifelse(
                                            foi_contact$h1_species == "Cattle",
                                            0.36, ifelse(
                                              foi_contact$h1_species == 
                                                "Red deer"|
                                                foi_contact$h1_species == 
                                                "Fallow deer",
                                              0.36, "ERROR"))))

# From kernel to FOI 
    foi_contact$foi <- foi_contact$kernel * foi_contact$beta * 
      foi_contact$lambda
    
# Variable with the interacting species
    foi_contact$interaction <- paste0(foi_contact$h1_species, "_from_", 
                                      foi_contact$h2_species)
    
# Summarizing FOI by dyads
    foi_sum_1 <- foi_contact[,c(1, 6:8, 12)] %>%
      group_by(hosts, h1_species, h2_species, interaction) %>% 
      summarise(total_kernel = sum(kernel))
    foi_sum_2 <- foi_contact[,c(6:8, 11:12)] %>%
      group_by(hosts, h1_species, h2_species, interaction) %>% 
      summarise(total_foi = sum(foi))
    foi_sum_3 <- foi_contact[,c(3, 6:8, 12)] %>%
      group_by(hosts, h1_species, h2_species, interaction) %>% 
      summarise(total_time = max(vart))
    foi_total <- merge(foi_sum_1, foi_sum_2) %>% merge(foi_sum_3)
    foi_total$hosts <- gsub('[SUFWSP]', '', foi_total$hosts)
    foi_total <- foi_total %>% 
      group_by(hosts, h1_species, h2_species, interaction) %>% 
      summarise(across(everything(), list(sum)))
    names(foi_total) <- gsub('_1', '', names(foi_total))
    
# Accounting for monitoring duration
    foi_total$rel_foi <- (foi_total$total_foi/foi_total$total_time)
    foi_total$rel_kernel <- (foi_total$total_kernel/foi_total$total_time)
    foi_total$loc <- m
    foi_total$tint <- n
    assign(paste0("foi_", substr(m, start = 1, stop = 2), "_",
                  substr(n, start = 1, stop = 2)), foi_total)
    }, silent = TRUE)
  }
}

6. Comparing risk among species pairs

We compared the FOI among species pairs in both study areas by means of brms (Bürkner, 2018), an R package for Bayesian modeling using the probabilistic programming language Stan (Carpenter et al., 2017).

6.1. FOI distribution

Firstly, we explored the data to select a distribution for the modeling. The FOI represents count, so we considered Poisson and Negative Binomial distribution.

family_test <- foi$rel_foi_int

k <- mean(family_test)^2/var(family_test); k # mean/variance

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
hist(rpois(n=999, lambda=mean(family_test)), main="Poisson")
hist(rnbinom(n=999, size=k, mu=mean(family_test)), main="Negative binomial")
hist(family_test, breaks=50, main="FOI")
mtext("Figure SC1. Data distribution", side = 3, line = - 1.5,outer = TRUE)

DNP data distribution

## [1] "Mean/variance= 0.135126854763587"                    
## [2] "Variance much higher than the mean -> Overdispersion"

SSP data distribution

## [1] "Mean/variance= 0.0258122890039858"                   
## [2] "Variance much higher than the mean -> Overdispersion"

In this case, the negative binomial distribution fits our data much better. Interspecific FOI data, especially when including wild animals, usually follow this distribution since most individuals are expected to have low interaction rates, but some individuals or species will have high interaction rates.

In addition, there were excess of zeros in the data, both in DNP and in SSP, which can be associated with two causes: (i) animals unable two interact, either because there are physical barriers separating them, such as fences; or (ii) because they have different home ranges. The first one can only occur in SSP, while the second may occur in both study areas. Therefore, a zero-inflated negative-binomial distribution could lead to a better fit of the model.

6.2. Accounting for spatial overlapping

Since some individuals could be unable to interact, either because there are physical barriers separating them, such as fences; or because they move within different zones, individuals without spatial overlap in their home ranges (95% Kernel Density Estimates) were excluded from the analysis to avoid biases. Intraspecific pairs of cattle and Iberian pig in SSP were also excluded, since the FOI between them could be due to interactions within the same group, thus it is not comparable with the rest of pairs, which belong to different groups.

# Home Range by Kernel
location = c("do", "ex")
for (j in location){
  dat <- get(paste0("dat_",j))
  dat$ID <- gsub('[SUFWSP].*', '', dat$ID)
  dat$X <- NULL
  
  kernel <- adehabitatHR::kernelUD(as(st_as_sf(dat, 
                                               coords = c("xcoord","ycoord"), 
                                               crs = "EPSG:25829"), 
                                      "Spatial")[,1], grid = 100,
                                   h = "href")
  kernel <- adehabitatHR::getverticeshr(kernel, percent=99, unin = "m", 
                                        unout="m", standardize=FALSE)
  kernel <- st_as_sf(kernel)
  op <- st_intersects(kernel, kernel)
  
  overlap <- data.frame(host1 = character(), host2 = character())
  
  for (m in 1:length(op)){
    overlap <- rbind(overlap,
                     data.frame(host1 = kernel$id[m], 
                                host2 = kernel$id[op[[m]]]))
  }
  overlap$hosts <- paste0(overlap$host1, "_from_", overlap$host2)
  assign(paste0("overlap_", j), overlap)
}
rm(dat,op,kernel,overlap, location, j,m)

# keep only overlapping pairs
foi_do_2h <- foi_do_2h[foi_do_2h$hosts %in% overlap_do$hosts,]
foi_ex_10 <- foi_ex_10[foi_ex_10$hosts %in% overlap_ex$hosts,]

# We also exclude Cattle-Cattle and Pig-Pig interactions in Extremadura (SSP)

In this case, values from different areas can be compared graphically to assess the differences in the species involved in disease dynamics. However, the results cannot be compared numerically because of the spatial resolution of the GPS, which was used as the spatial range for transmission in the relative risk of transmission modeling. MoveSTIR considers \(λ\) as the amount of pathogen deposited per unit of time in the spatial range, that is, the larger the spatial range considered, the lower the amount of pathogen per surface area, and consequently, the lower the exposure of the acquirers. This does not affect the relative estimations obtained when employing the same spatial range for transmission, but it does have an effect when using different spatial ranges.

7. Accounting for location fix interval

The code shown in this appendix is not intended for being reproduced with other telemetry data, so mandatory changes are not indicated. Nonetheless, the code can be run with other data if modified properly.

7.1. FOI estimates accuracy

To investigate the effect of the interval at which GPS records locations, we followed these steps:

  1. First, we subsampled the SSP trajectories (see Appendix 1) at fix intervals of 10, 15, 20, 30, 45, 60, 90, 120, 180, 360, and 720 minutes.
  2. Next, we modeled the relative risk among individuals using moveSTIR (see Appendix 3; Wilber et al., 2022)..
  3. We loaded the trajectories using the loop described in Appendix 5, with the values location = "extremadura" and tint = paste0(c(10, 15, 20, 30, 45, 60, 90, 120, 180, 360, 720), "min"), and combined them into a single object called foi_tint.
  4. We modeled the FOI in each fix interval subsample following a negative-binomial distribution, with the pair of interacting species as the predictor.
# Converting response variable in integer and time to numeric
foi_tint$rel_foi_int <- as.integer(foi_tint$rel_foi*10^10)
foi_tint$interaction <- as.factor(foi_tint$interaction)
foi_tint$tint_min <- as.numeric(gsub("min", "", foi_tint$tint))

# Cleaning the environment
rm(list=setdiff(ls(), c("foi_tint", "dat_ex")))

# Negative binomial modeling for each sampling interval
tint_list <- list()
for (i in unique(foi_tint$tint_min)){
  f <- foi_tint[foi_tint$tint_min == i,] %>%
    group_by(interaction) %>%
    summarise_at(vars(rel_foi_int), list(rel_foi_int = mean))
  f2 <- f[f$rel_foi_int != 0,]$interaction
  brm_fit <- brm(rel_foi_int ~ 0 + interaction,
                 data = foi_tint[foi_tint$tint_min == i & 
                                   foi_tint$interaction %in% f2,],
                 family = negbinomial(), chains = 4, iter = 12000, 
                 warmup = 5000, control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95, 
                                               max_treedepth = 14))
  a <- data.frame(fixef(brm_fit)) # Storing Estimates and confidence intervals
  a$interaction <- gsub("interaction", "", row.names(a))
  f3 <- data.frame(interaction = f[f$rel_foi_int == 0,]$interaction)
  a <- merge(a, f3, all = T)
  a[is.na(a)] <- 0
  a$tint <- i
  nlist <- paste0("tint_", i)
  tint_list[[nlist]] <- a
}

tint <- Reduce(rbind, tint_list)
tint$interaction <- gsub(" ", "", tint$interaction)

The ´tint´ object now includes the estimated coefficients for each species pair in each of the time intervals considered.

  1. We divided these estimates by the estimate obtained from the 10-minute time interval data to obtain the proportional accuracy of each time interval relative to the highest resolution time interval. Therefore, the proportional accuracy for a time interval of \(t\) minutes was calculated as follows::

\[ Proportional\text{ }accuracy_t = estimate_t/estimate_{10} \]

tint <- tint[order(tint$tint),]%>%
  group_by(interaction) %>%
  mutate(relative_est = Estimate/first(Estimate))
tint[is.na(tint)] <- 0
  1. We categorized the results into three groups based on the interaction rates between species pairs, based on the approach of Triguero-Ocaña et al. (2021): (i) High interaction rate pairs, which included intraspecific pairs and red deer-cattle pairs, (ii) Moderate interaction rate pairs, which included red deer-pig and red deer-wild boar pairs, and (iii) Low interaction rate pairs, which comprised the remaining pairs of species.
tint$risk_group <- ifelse(tint$interaction == "Cow_from_Cow" |

7.2. Exposure pattern in the temporal window

In addition, we computed the relative exposure between each pair of individuals in the temporal window. This refers to the FOI from the depositor to the acquirer at each moment of the temporal window since pathogen deposition divided by the total FOI between the depositor and the acquirer (see Appendix 3) .

To help understand this, let’s consider an example: imagine two individuals, A and B, and we want to estimate B’s exposure from A. For simplicity, we won’t consider spatial resolution and will assume that \(λ = 1\text{ } hour^{-1}\), \(β = 0.5\text{ }hour^{-1}\), and a linear pathogen decay of \(v = 0.01\text{ }hour^{-1}\).

In the first part of the example, let’s suppose that A and B only share a foraging location (e.g., a feeding trough), without any other interactions. On the first night, A goes to the trough and stays there for 3 hours, depositing 3 units of pathogen. The amount of pathogen after \(t\) period of time will be \(P_t = 1-(0.01·t) + 1·(0.01·(t-1)) + 1·(0.01·(t-2))\). On the second night, at the same time, B goes to the same trough. The amount of pathogen at the time it arrives (\(t=24\text{ }hours\)) would be \(P_{24} = 2.31\). If B stays at the trough for three hours, its pathogen acquisition would be \(β·P = 0.5·(P_{24} + P_{25} + P_{26}) = 1.83\). If the sampling interval is 10 minutes, we can monitor this interaction perfectly. However, as the sampling interval widens, it becomes more difficult to accurately estimate the exposure. With a sampling interval of 2 hours, two things can happen: we can get just one location of A and B at the trough, assuming two hours of deposition and acquisition, and thus underestimating the exposure, or we can get two locations, assuming four hours of deposition and acquisition, and overestimating the exposure. With a sampling interval of 6 hours, we may either not detect the interaction or overestimate it.

By visually exploring the relative exposure between each pair of individuals in the temporal window, we can identify exposure patterns, and the differences in the accuracy among sampling intervals may be disclosed.

8. Spatial representation of the FOI

8.1. Extracting spatial FOI

We created and R function called spatial_risk which calculates the FOI in each pixel according to 5 arguments:

  • foi: A dataframe with columns foi, with FOI values and t indicating date and time.
  • traj: A dataframe with columns timeindicating date and time, and xand yindicating the coordinates.
  • res: The resolution of the output raster in crsunits.
  • method: “cumulative” or “average”, for calculating the sum or the mean of the FOI in each pixel
  • crs: indicating the Coordinate Reference System in which xand y are provided in trajobject.

The function returns a raster with resresolution and crs Coordinate Reference System.

spatial_risk <- function(foi, traj, res, method, crs){
  # Assign coordinates and transform into spatial object
  foi_coord = merge(foi, traj, all.x =TRUE)
  foi_vect = vect(foi_coord, geom=c("x", "y"), crs=crs)
  
  # Raster to plot the values
  r_template = terra::rast(xmin = min(traj$x), xmax = max(traj$x), 
                           ymin = min(traj$y), ymax = max(traj$y),
                           crs = crs, 
                           resolution = res)
  
  # Rasterize foi values
  spatial_foi = rasterize(foi_vect, r_template, field = "foi",
                           fun = ifelse(method == "cumulative", sum, 
                                        ifelse(method == "average", mean,
                                               print("Error: Method must be 
                                                     cumulative or average"))),
                           na.rm = TRUE)
  return(spatial_foi)
}

# Then we ran the function for all the wildlife-livestock pairs and save the 
# raster file.

      list_loc <- split(foi_spatial , f = foi_spatial$host1)
      assign(paste0("fois_time_", m), list_loc)
      
      # We create a dataframe with all the CTMM trajectories
      all_traj <- Reduce(rbind, ctmm_list)
      assign(paste0("ctmm_traj_", m), all_traj)
      
      # Delete unnecessary objects
      rm(list = c("foi_contact", "foi_spatial", "list_loc", "foi_list", 
                  "ctmm_data", "dat", "all_traj", "a", "ctmm_list"))
    }, silent = TRUE)
  }
}


for (j in location) {
  list_spatial <- list()      # Empty list
  for (i in names(get(paste0("fois_time_", j)))){
    fois_spatial <- get(paste0("fois_time_", j))[[i]]
    
    # Keeping the wildlife FOI from livestock and livestock FOI from wildlife
    # Other values are not considered
    if (fois_spatial[1,]$host1_group == "Livestock") {
      fois_spatial <- fois_spatial[fois_spatial$host2_group == "Wildlife",]
    }
    if (fois_spatial[1,]$host1_group == "Wildlife") {
      fois_spatial <- fois_spatial[fois_spatial$host2_group == "Livestock",]
    }
    
    # Applying the function
    fois_spatial_rast <- spatial_risk(foi = fois_spatial, 
                                 traj = get(paste0("ctmm_traj_", j)),
                                 res = 50, 
                                 method = "cumulative", 
                                 crs = "EPSG:25829")
    
    # Saving in a list
    nlist <- paste0(i, "_", fois_spatial$host1_group[[1]])
    list_spatial[[nlist]] <- fois_spatial_rast
  }
  
  # Sum rasters and compute the proportion
  list_spatial <- terra::app(terra::rast(list_spatial), sum, na.rm = TRUE)

  list_spatial <- 100*list_spatial/terra::global(list_spatial,
                                                 fun = "sum", 
                                                 na.rm = TRUE)[[1]]
  
  # Saving the output
  assign(paste0("spat_foi_interface_", j), list_spatial)
    terra::writeRaster(list_spatial, paste0("spat_foi_interface_", j, ".tif"), 
                     filetype = "GTiff", overwrite = TRUE)
  
  rm(list = c("fois_spatial", "fois_spatial_rast", "list_spatial"))
}

8.2. Home Ranges estimation

For the estimation of the Home Ranges, we used 95% Kernel Density Estimation.

for (j in location){
    kernel <- adehabitatHR::kernelUD(as(st_as_sf(get(paste0("ctmm_traj_", j)), 
                                                 coords = c("x","y"), 
                                                 crs = "EPSG:25829"), 
                                        "Spatial")[,1], grid = 80,
                                     h = "href")
    kernel <- adehabitatHR::getverticeshr(kernel, percent=95, unin = "m", 
                                          unout="m", standardize=FALSE)
    
    # For adding species and "Livestock"/"Wildlife" labels
    kernel <- get(paste0("dat_", substr(j, start = 1, stop = 2)))[,c("ID", "SP"),] %>% 
      mutate(ID = sub("(\\d)[^0-9].*", "\\1", ID)) %>% 
      mutate(group = case_when(SP == "Cow" ~ "Livestock",
                               SP == "Pig" ~ "Livestock",
                               TRUE ~ "Wildlife")) %>% unique() %>%
      merge(st_as_sf(kernel), ., all.x = TRUE, by.x = "id", by.y = "ID")
    
    assign(paste0("HR_", j), kernel)
    
    st_write(kernel, paste0("HR_", j, ".shp"), driver = "ESRI Shapefile",
             delete_dsn = TRUE)
    
    rm("kernel")
}
